[1] Cases in various countries:
Americas
---
WHO/PAHO Epidemiological Update Dengue and other Arboviruses
Date: Wed 10 Jun 2020
https://www.paho.org/en/documents/epidemiological-update-dengue-and-other-arboviruses-10-june-2020


In the Region of the Americas, between epidemiological week (EW) 1 and EW 21 of 2020 [1 Jan-23 May 2020], a total of 1 645 678 cases of arboviral disease were reported. Of those, 1600 947 (97.3%) were dengue cases, 37 279 were chikungunya cases, and 7 452 were Zika cases (figure 1 [all figures available at the source URL above]).

In the Region of the Americas, the total number of cases of arboviral disease reported in 2020 as of EW 21 of 2020 represents an approximate 10% relative decrease compared with the same period in 2019, which was an epidemic year (figure 2).

Between EW 1 and EW 21 of 2020, a total of 7452 cases of Zika have been reported, including one death (reported in Brazil), in the Region of the Americas.

The highest proportions of cases in the Region were reported in the following countries: Brazil with 6387 cases (86% of cases in the Region), Bolivia with 537 cases (8.4%), and Guatemala with 133 cases (2%). Since its 1st detection in Brazil in March of 2015, local transmission of Zika has been confirmed in all countries and territories in the Americas, except for continental Chile, Uruguay, and Canada. In 2016, a total of 651 590 cases were reported, and a significant reduction in transmission was observed in [subsequent] years (figure 5 [Distribution of reported cases of Zika by epidemiological week. Region of the Americas, 2019-2020 (up to EW 21 of 2020)]).

[Maps showing the location of the affected countries in the Americas mentioned above and below can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7568400,35574;
Central America at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7568400,39455;
South America at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7568400,6186. - Mod.TY]

Imported cases with little or no possibility of ongoing mosquito transmission
---
- Ireland (Dublin): congenital, ex Brazil. 11 Jun 2020. (confirmed) 1st baby born in Ireland with congenital Zika infection. The baby's mother was in her native Brazil during the 1st trimester of pregnancy; Zika virus was detected in her blood at 11 weeks into her pregnancy but was no longer detected at 31 weeks' gestation. At birth, the baby was diagnosed with severe microcephaly, but the examination was otherwise normal. At 14 months the baby developed epilepsy, quadriplegic cerebral palsy, visual impairment, and showed severe global developmental delay.
https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/medics-confirm-first-case-of-baby-born-in-ireland-with-a-congenital-zika-infection-1.4276892

