[4] African lineage comes to Brazil
Date: Mon 1 Jun 2020
Source: Int J Infect Dis. 96:579-581 DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijid.2020.05.090 [edited]
https://www.ijidonline.com/article/S1201-9712(20)30397-0/pdf


ref: Kasprzykowski JI, Fukutani KF, Fabio H, et al. A recursive sub-typing screening surveillance system detects the arising of the ZIKV African lineage in Brazil: Is there risk of a new epidemic? [published online ahead of print, 2020 Jun 1]. Int J Infect Dis. 2020; S1201-9712(20)30397-0. doi:10.1016/j.ijid.2020.05.090
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Highlights
- The Brazilian sequence ZIKV lineage proportion changed across 5 years.
- The automated surveillance system helps identify ZIKV molecular epidemiology.
- A new lineage emerged in Brazil and could be a potential risk of a new epidemic.

Abstract
--------
There is currently no system to track the emergence of Zika virus (ZIKV) subtypes. We developed a surveillance system able to retrieve sequence submissions and further classify distinct ZIKV genotypes in the world. This approach was able to detect a new occurrence of ZIKV from an African lineage in Brazil in 2019.

[Results and discussion]
------------------------
Our approach also identified the emergence of 5.4% of all sequences from 2019 classified as African lineage (in January and in May). The difference in the distribution of these proportions over time was statistically significant, revealing a substantial change in ZIKV sequence submissions (figure 1B). These African lineages were isolated from 2 different regions of Brazil: South, from the Rio Grande do Sul (Almeida et al, 2020) and Southeast, from Rio de Janeiro (Alencar et al, 2020) and were from 2 different sources: one was isolated from the _Aedes albopictus_ mosquito species (Alencar et al, 2020) and the other from _Alouatta guariba_, a monkey species (Almeida et al, 2020). The geographic distance between these 2 different regions of Brazil is more than 1500 km [932 mi]. The distinct localities and different sources of isolation are of concern and suggest that this African lineage could have already been circulating in Brazil for a significant period. Note that the phylogenetic-based typing tool confirmed the classification.

--
communicated by:
Roland Hübner
Superior Health Council
Brussels
Belgium
<roland.hubner@sante.belgique.be>

[This report provides evidence that an African lineage of Zika virus had become established in Brazil in at least 2 locations. With the Almeida et al. (reference below) finding that lineage in 9 howler monkeys they raise the possibility that this Zika virus lineage is maintained in a sylvan (forest) transmission cycle involving the monkeys in much the same way that yellow fever is in Brazil. That means that eradication of Zika virus there will not be possible with currently available technology. This is not good news.

Reference
---------
de Almeida PR, Ehlers LP, Demoliner M, AKA Eisen et al. Detection of a novel African-lineage-like Zika virus naturally infecting free-living neotropical primates in Southern Brazil. bioRxiv, 2019; https://doi.org/10.1101/828871.
- Mod.TY]
